PREPARE THE DATA

We load the data and the base map

# DATA
datos <- read.xlsx("C:/Users/menci/OneDrive/Escritorio/R STUDIO/DATA VISUALIZATION/TRABAJO FINAL/migraciones_final.xlsx", sheet = 1)

# BASE MAP
mapa_mundial <- st_as_sf(getMap(resolution = "low"))
mapa_mundial <- mapa_mundial |>
  rename(Country = ADMIN)

Then we join our data (and change some country names)

datos_mapa <- mapa_mundial |>
  left_join(datos, by = "Country")

datos_mapa <- datos_mapa |>
  mutate(Country = recode(Country, "United Arab Emirates" = "EAU"),
         Country = recode(Country, "British Virgin Islands" = "BVI"))

We create the brackets for the “% of immigrants”

datos_mapa$Percent_Migration <- datos_mapa$Percent_Migration * 100

datos_mapa$Percent_Migration_category <- cut(
  datos_mapa$Percent_Migration,
  breaks = c(-Inf, 1, 3, 10, 25, Inf),
  labels = c("< 1%", "1% - 3%", "3% - 10%", "10% - 25%", ">25%"),
  right = FALSE
)

We create the first MAP

original_map <- ggplot(datos_mapa) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Percent_Migration_category), color = "white", linewidth = 0.25) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("< 1%" = "#ebc657", "1% - 3%" = "#aac25c","3% - 10%" = "#72b56e", 
               "10% - 25%" = "#388f8d", ">25%" = "#286b80"),
    name = "% de población migrante",
    na.value = "#e1e1e1",
    na.translate = FALSE,
    guide = guide_legend(
      keywidth = 0.7,  # Legend width
      keyheight = 0.7, # Legend height
    )
  ) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.17, 0.28),  # Legend position
    legend.justification = c(0, 0), 
    legend.title = element_blank(), 
    legend.text = element_text(size = 8 , family = "raleway"))+
  coord_sf()+
  theme(aspect.ratio = 0.6)

We create the BARPLOT

barplot <- datos_mapa |>
  arrange(desc(Percent_Migration)) |>
  head(8) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Country, Percent_Migration), y = Percent_Migration, fill = Percent_Migration)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="#8aa526",  width = 0.7) +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = paste0(round(Percent_Migration), "%")),
    hjust = 0,  # Text position
    nudge_y = 4, #Space between bars and percentage
    size = 2,
    family = "raleway"
  )+
  coord_flip() +  # Horizontal
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.05)))+ #Space between bars
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_blank(),  # Eliminate text in axis X
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8,  margin = margin(r = 15)),   # Margin (for the flags)
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),  # Eliminate the title in axis X
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),  # Eliminate the title in axis X
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none",
    aspect.ratio = 1.8 #more or less compressed
  )
barplot

FINAL REPLICATION

Now we want to join the map with the barplot and add the logo, title and source. So first we load the images for the logo and image and transform the map and barplot into a grob plot. The grob command allows us to directly manipulate graphical elements so it’ss useful for combining complex plots outside of standard ggplot2 capabilities:

#We load the logo and image to add
logo <- readPNG("C:/Users/menci/OneDrive/Escritorio/R STUDIO/DATA VISUALIZATION/TRABAJO FINAL/EOM.png")
image <- readPNG ("C:/Users/menci/OneDrive/Escritorio/R STUDIO/DATA VISUALIZATION/TRABAJO FINAL/familia2.png")

#Transform into grob
map_grob <- ggplotGrob(original_map)
graph_grob <- ggplotGrob(graph)

We join map + barplot + source + images + title:

IMPROVEMENTS

Once we have done the entire replication, we are going to improve this map by:

  1. Spliting the numerical scale of migration in other categories, specifically, I split the “10-25%” category into two categories: “10-15%” and “15-25%”. IÑAKI’S ADVICE: try to make the scale continuous so we don’t have to choose categories. (I’ll do this at the end of the script but in this case I keep my original improvement)
  1. Add another barplot for the countries with less immigrants
  1. Adding migratory flows (differenciating flows depending on the reason of migration). I used the “Migration Report 2017” and the information OF the Mexican Government (2017-2024) to choose the most important migratory flows in 2017 on the political, social and economic sphere.

We prepare FLOWS to add to the map

I did it manually. First we define the flows by origin and destination

#define flows
flows <- data.frame(
  Origin = c("Libya","Marruecos", "Argelia", "El Salvador", 
             "Honduras", "Mexico", "Ethiopia", "Venezuela", 
             "Siria", "Siria", "Siria", "Siria", "India", "India", "Egypt", 
             "Australia", "Venezuela", "Venezuela", "China"),
  Destination = c("Italy", "Spain", "France", "United States", 
                  "United States1", "United States2", "Saudi Arabia", 
                  "Colombia", "Turkey", "Lebanon", "Jordan", "Iraq", "Saudi Arabia1",
                  "Oman", "Saudi Arabia2", "Europe", "Brasil", "Peru", "Europe1")
)

I set the coordinates manually to specify the exact area where I wanted the arrow to reach

# coords: manually set
country_coords <- data.frame(
  country = c("Libya", "Marruecos", "Argelia", "El Salvador", "Honduras", 
              "Mexico", "Ethiopia", "Venezuela", "Siria", "Italy", "Spain", 
              "France", "United States", "Saudi Arabia", "Colombia", "Turkey", 
              "Lebanon", "Jordan", "Iraq", "India", "Oman", "Egypt", "Australia", "Europe",
              "Brasil", "Peru", "United States2", "United States1", "Saudi Arabia2", "Saudi Arabia1",
              "China", "Europe1"),
  lon = c(17.228, -7.092, 1.659, -88.896, -86.241,-102.5528, 40.48, -65.589, 
          38.996, 12.567, -3.749, 2.2137, -95.712, 45.0792, -74.2973, 35.2433, 
          35.8623, 30.5851, 43.6792, 78.96288, 55.9232, 30.8024, 133.775, 6.129,
          -51.925, -75.015152, -110, -85, 43, 42.5, 104.19, 19.129),  # Longitudes
  lat = c(26.3351, 31.7917, 28.0339, 13.7942, 15.199,  23.6345, 9.145, 7.4238, 
          32.0, 41.8719, 40.463, 46.2276, 37.090, 22.8859, 4.5709, 38.9637, 
          33.8547, 36.2384,  33.2231, 20.5936, 21.5125, 26.8205, -25.2743, 49.8152,
          -14.235004, -9.189967, 39.090, 40, 27, 24, 35.86, 51.8152)    # Latitudes
)

Then I added the coordinates (latitude and longitude) of the origin and destination countries to the flows

flows <- flows |>
  left_join(country_coords, by = c("Origin" = "country")) |>
  rename(origin_lon = lon, origin_lat = lat) |>
  left_join(country_coords, by = c("Destination" = "country"))|>
  rename(dest_lon = lon, dest_lat = lat)

Finally I set the reason of migration

flows <- flows |>
  mutate(
    reason = case_when(
      Origin %in% c("Libya", "El Salvador", "Honduras", "Venezuela", "Siria") ~ "Violence / War",
      TRUE ~ "Economic Reasons"
    )
  )

We create the MAP WITH IMPROVEMENTS

Wecreate the new categories (and colors), then we add the flows over the map with the new categories

#New categories
datos_mapa$Percent_Migration_category <- cut(
 datos_mapa$Percent_Migration,
 breaks = c(-Inf, 1, 3, 10, 15, 25, Inf),
 labels = c("< 1%", "1% - 3%", "3% - 10%", "10% - 15%", "15% - 25%", ">25%"),
 right = FALSE)

map_2 <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = datos_mapa, 
          aes(fill = Percent_Migration_category), 
          color = "white", linewidth = 0.2) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c(
      "< 1%" = "#e0f7fa",
      "1% - 3%" = "#80deea",
      "3% - 10%" = "#26c6da",
      "10% - 15%" = "#3498db",
      "15% - 25%" = "#1d62ad",
      ">25%" = "#1a5276"
    ),
    name = "% of immigrants *",
    na.translate = FALSE,
    na.value = "gray80" 
  ) +
  
  # Flechas con efecto de grosor manual
  geom_curve(data = flows, 
             aes(x = origin_lon, y = origin_lat, 
                 xend = dest_lon, yend = dest_lat, 
                 color = reason), 
             curvature = 0.3,  # Arrow curvature
             arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.08, "inches"), type = "open"), 
             linewidth = 0.7,  #Arrow line width
             lineend = "round") +
  geom_curve(data = flows, 
             aes(x = origin_lon, y = origin_lat, 
                 xend = dest_lon, yend = dest_lat, 
                 color = reason), 
             curvature = 0.3,  
             arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.08, "inches"), type = "open"), 
             linewidth = 1.4,  #Effect line width
             alpha = 0.3,   
             lineend = "round") +
  
  # Reasons of migration
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("Violence / War" = "#f77d00", 
               "Economic Reasons" = "#9800f7"),
    name = "Reason of migration"
  ) +
  
  # Theme and legens
  theme_void() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.18, 0.4),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 8, face = "bold", family = "raleway"),
    legend.key.size = unit(0.07, "cm"),
    legend.key.height = unit(0.17, "cm"),
    legend.key.width = unit(0.17, "cm"),
    legend.box.spacing = unit(0.07, "cm"),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 8, family = "raleway"),
    aspect.ratio = 0.6
  ) +
  coord_sf()

map_2

MAP WITH IÑAKI’S ADVICE

Here I tried to apply Iñaki’s advice (professor) to improve the plot, specifically I take into account these suggestion:

  1. Avoid categories and make the “% of immigrants” continuous since we have this data.

  2. Flip the color scale (blue for low values and yellow for high values)

PROBLEM: If we do the plot continuous the map would look blue because the mayority of countries have less than 25% of immigration, as we can see:

linear_scale_colors <- scale_fill_gradientn(
  colors = c("#286b80", "#388f8d", "#72b56e", "#aac25c", "#eef100"), 
  na.value = "gray80",  
  name = "% of immigrants",  
  limits = c(0, 100),
  breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75, 100),
  labels = c("0%", "25%", "50%", "75%", "100%")  
)

map_cont <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = datos_mapa, 
          aes(fill = Percent_Migration), 
          color = "white", linewidth = 0.2)+
  theme_void() +
  linear_scale_colors+
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.2, 0.4),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold"),
    legend.key.size = unit(0.15, "cm"),
    legend.key.height = unit(0.25, "cm"),
    legend.key.width = unit(0.25, "cm"),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 8),
    aspect.ratio = 0.6
  ) +
  coord_sf()

map_cont

In this map we can not see differences between countries, only in the Arabian zone where immigration is notably higher. That’s because we are using a continuous scale. A better option would be a logarithmic scale since it would better highlight variations across regions with lower immigration rates. So, we could

log_scale_colors <- scale_fill_gradientn(
  colors = c("#286b80", "#388f8d", "#72b56e", "#aac25c", "#eef100"), 
  trans = "log10",  # logarithmic scale
  na.value = "gray80",  
  limits = c(0.01, 100),
  name = "% of immigrants",  
  breaks = c(0.01, 1, 5, 25, 100),  #since it's logarithmic we can not star from 0
  labels = c("0.01%", "1%", "5%", "25%", "100%")  
)

# logarithmic MAP
map_log <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = datos_mapa, 
          aes(fill = Percent_Migration), 
          color = "white", linewidth = 0.2) +
  log_scale_colors +
  theme_void() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.2, 0.4),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 8, face = "bold"),
    legend.key.size = unit(0.15, "cm"),
    legend.key.height = unit(0.25, "cm"),
    legend.key.width = unit(0.25, "cm"),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 6),
    aspect.ratio = 0.6
  ) +
  coord_sf()

map_log

QUESTIONS

Before continuing the plot (joining it with the bar plots), what do you think about the logarithmic scale? I think that thanks to it we can highight better the differences than with the continuous scale. Also, I think it’s better -as you said- that the blue and dark colors are related to lower values and the higher values are represented with more lighter and yellowish colors.

However I see a certain limitation with a logarithmic scale than with a categorical scale: when we see the map and look at a countrie, for example Chad (Africa), we can know that it has a green color but we can doubt the percentage of immigration since we can think that it has between 7% and 20% of immigration approximately, while with the previous continuous scale (the original or the one I improved) we know for sure that the % of immigration is between 3 and 10%, which is somewhat more exact.

Other example: if we see Canada we could also have some doubts about the € of immigration, while with the categorical scale it’s clear that it’s more clear that it has between 15 and 25% of immigration

What do you think? Maybe is there another type of scale beyond continuous, logarithmic or categorical that better suits the map? Or
